{
    "intent": "explaining",
    "response": "Imagine you're trying to order food from a restaurant, but they keep having issues with their kitchen. They might get slammed with orders or have equipment problems. To help them handle this, you give them some extra time to prepare your meal, and then some more if they still need it. That's kind of what the retry policy does for computer systems. It gives them a little more time to try again when something goes wrong, so that they can handle times when things get really busy or broken. This helps reduce the load on the system so it doesn't get overwhelmed and break down completely." , "tone": "informative" , "key_points": ["retry policy", "exponential backoff", "upstream services"] , "constraints_followed": ["Chat & Generation JSON schema"] , "risks_or_caveats": [] }

temp_1.0_output:
{
  "intent": "explain",
  "response": "Here's how it works: Imagine you're trying to order food from a restaurant, but their servers are slow. To help you get your food faster, they start giving you hints on when to try again. At first, they tell you to wait for 1 second before trying again. If the server is still slow after that, they'll say to wait for 2 seconds next time, then 4 seconds, and so on. This way, you'll get your food faster without overwhelming the restaurant's servers.\n\nIn programming, this idea is used in something called exponential backoff. It helps systems recover from problems like when a network connection is slow or when a server is down. The goal is to make it easier for these systems to come back online and handle more requests over time."
  , "tone": "friendly", "key_points": [
    "Helps systems recover quickly after problems"
], "constraints_followed": ["returnOnlyValidJSONMatchingTheSchema"] , "risks_or_caveats": [""]}

